About
With works ranging from Antiquity to the early 20th century, the Founder’s Collection comprises more than six thousand pieces gathered throughout Calouste Sarkis Gulbenkian’s life, including Egyptian Art, Greco-Roman Art, Islamic Arts, Painting, Sculpture and European Decorative Arts. Works by great masters such as Rubens, Rembrandt, Turner, Degas and René Lalique’s largest set of jewels are just a few examples of what can be found in one of the best private collections in the world. Besides the Founder’s Collection, the Calouste Gulbenkian Museum is also comprised by the Modern Collection, which features the largest and most complete collection of modern and contemporary Portuguese Art. The Calouste Gulbenkian Museum is surrounded by one of the most emblematic modern gardens in Portugal, open all year. The Museum offers a wide range of facilities to improve the visitor’s experience: three cafeterias overlooking the Garden, a museum shop, free cloackroom service and free Wi-Fi.
Duration: 1-2 hours

  • satipatipatti
    Atlanta, Georgia419 contributions
    Our favorite touristy art overload of our trip
    The admission to the museum is very reasonable. We decided on a whim to stop in one Monday which was fortunate because they are closed on Tuesdays. There will be other reviewers who will describe the various stunning and precious objects on display: an amazing trove for one man to collect, but there is one thing that stood out as absolutely amazing. Calouste Gulbenkian must have been after the most pristine collectible items. There were vessels of glass in the collection that were 3000 years old and they were in perfect condition, not a chip, crack or scrape was present. While the top-level museums such as New York’s Metropolitan have collections of ancient Greek kratera and amphorae, they are overwhelming cracked or bearing restoration patches with very few undamaged items. Gulbenkian turned this manner of collecting on its head by acquiring only the most perfectly preserved pottery, metalware and other items from many cultures with very few distressed pieces on display. See the accompanying picture of a Greek bell krater with basal handles. Any imperfections visible are actually lights reflecting off of the glass. Similarly, the white jade tankard with gold-riveted handle is flawless and is 620 years old. There is enough here for two trips. While this is a tourist destination it is large enough to accommodate large numbers of people without feeling crowded.
    Visited November 2023
    Traveled as a couple

Mary C
Bristol, UK14 contributions
No filler - best art museum in lisbon
Oct 2024 • Couples
Take the metro to San Sebastiao from town centre - only takes 10 minutes and you can pay with contact less debit card. The museum itself was 10 euros each without any discounts and very well worth it. If you want to linger over everything it's a 2 hour visit, but if you're for example only really interested in the paintings and not so fussed about some of the jewellery for example its an hour to 90 minutes. I appreciate some people will love the jewellery! The exhibition is arranged chronologically starting in ancient Egpyt with sculpture and objects, then a small Greco-Roman collection, a little from Assyria and then onto Persian carpets and other artefacts - some very interesting Arabic scientific texts and items from China and Japan. Then some absolutely incredible French gothic ivories - things of rare beauty from 800 years ago. You then are in European Art - early Flemish works, Rembrandt, Rubens, Van Dyck, Franz Hals, Turner and then onto the impressionists. Each artist named represented by one or two works but what works. This is really worth it. Small gift shop, cafeteria , cloak room and bathrooms on site set in nice gardens. This is small but perfectly formed.
Written October 6, 2024

Abby D
Atlanta, GA124 contributions
You Can Cover the Museum in a Reasonable Amount of Time
Sep 2024 • Family
We took the train from Baixa to get here. I love that the museum is tucked away in gardens. There benches outside where you sit and enjoy time outside in semi-privacy.

You have to get your bag checked before entering and, as expected, food and drink are not allowed in. They have a coat check where you can store your things for free. They also have lockers that you get use for 1 euro, which you get back, The security guard was being a bit ridiculous and told me I had to check my lotion. I can’t imagine he’s doing that to every person that comes in with lotion. In fact, he said nothing about the lotion in my mom’s purse.

The art and the artifacts were from Europe and Asia. The museum was quite small but I liked the fact that I could get through all of the pieces in a a reasonable time.

The last exhibit was my favorite with the ancient (vintage?) hairpieces and jewelry.

The ducks in the garden were quite nice.
